  "narrative": {
    "intro": "Through FY2026 to date, federal contract obligations in Rhode Island total $512M; current-year totals are partial (fiscal year to date). Obligations are down 43.6% year over year from prior periods. The state received 3,386 awards with an average award size of $151K. Year-to-date buying is heavily concentrated: the Department of Defense accounts for $412M of obligations, followed by the Department of Veterans Affairs at $49.9M and the Department of Homeland Security at $16.4M. Top vendors include RAYTHEON COMPANY at $79.5M and SEACORP, LLC at $54.7M, with RITE-SOLUTIONS, INC. at $33.7M and MCLAUGHLIN RESEARCH CORPORATION at $25.6M also in the top ranks. Engineering Services leads industries with $170M in obligations, while Ammunition (except Small Arms) Manufacturing and Research and Development in the Physical, Engineering, and Life Sciences (except Nanotechnology and Biotechnology) record $71.4M and $42.8M respectively. FY2026 to date obligations of $512M follow prior fiscal year totals of $908M in FY25 and $1.2B in both FY22 and FY24.",
    "sections": [
      {
        "heading": "How concentrated is federal spending in Rhode Island?",
        "body": "Spending is highly concentrated: the Department of Defense accounts for $412M of FY2026 to date obligations. The next two agencies, the Department of Veterans Affairs and the Department of Homeland Security, account for $49.9M and $16.4M respectively. Overall obligations for FY2026 to date are $512M, down 43.6% year over year."
      },
      {
        "heading": "Which vendors and industries capture the most obligations in FY2026 to date?",
        "body": "Top vendors are led by RAYTHEON COMPANY at $79.5M and SEACORP, LLC at $54.7M, with RITE-SOLUTIONS, INC. at $33.7M and MCLAUGHLIN RESEARCH CORPORATION at $25.6M. Engineering Services is the largest industry at $170M, followed by Ammunition (except Small Arms) Manufacturing at $71.4M and Research and Development in the Physical, Engineering, and Life Sciences (except Nanotechnology and Biotechnology) at $42.8M."
      }
